    (author) Edward Albee
    (category) Quote
    (date) 2026-07-18
    (link) https://edwardalbeesociety.org/works/tiny-alice/
    (rating) 5
    (slug) every-monster-was-a-man-first
    (title) "Every monster was a man first."
    (updated) 2026-07-18
    (description) A line from Edward Albee's Tiny Alice (1964) that the internet has flattened into a compassion slogan. Restored to a play about an innocent dismantled by polite, well-dressed people, it reads colder: monstrousness isn't a separate species but a destination, and the load-bearing word is "first" — there was a man, then there was a monster, and Albee never tells you what happened in between.
  > (item)
    (author) Socrates · Ben Jonson
    (category) Quote
    (date) 2026-06-11
    (link)
    (rating) 5
    (slug) speak-that-i-may-see-thee
    (title) "Speak, that I may see thee."
    (updated) 2026-06-11
    (description) An ancient line attributed to Socrates — recorded by Apuleius, passed down through Petrarch and Erasmus, and given its famous English form by Ben Jonson in Timber: or, Discoveries (1641): "Language most shows a man; speak that I may see thee." The idea: a face shows a body, but speech shows a mind — a person stays invisible until they talk.
  > (item)
    (author) Herbert A. Simon
    (category) Quote
    (date) 2026-06-07
    (link)
    (rating) 5
    (slug) poverty-of-attention
    (title) "A wealth of information creates a poverty of attention."
    (updated) 2026-06-07
    (description) Herbert Simon's 1971 line — the origin of "the attention economy." Once information becomes abundant, it stops being the scarce resource; the new bottleneck is attention, the finite thing information consumes. So the real skill shifts from finding information to choosing what to ignore.
